<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-793-686  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 793 686.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>The New York Times  Oct 25 1989 v139 pC2(N) pD2(L) 14 col in.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Unleashing Ma Bell. (AT and T seeks freedom to regulate its ownprices) (Economic Scene) (column)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Passell, Peter.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>AT and T is appealing to the FCC in hopes that thetelecommunications giant will be able to reduce its prices andhang on to its clientele.andP;  When the telephone monopoly was brokenup in 1984, the FCC regulated AT and T heavily to keep it fromputting other long-distance telephone companies out of business.andO;Since 1984, MCI Communications and US Sprint have grown so muchthat they now endanger AT and T's customer base.andP;  In 1988, the FCCallowed AT and T to switch to a price-cap system that lets thecompany adjust individual rates within in a narrow range.andP;  AT andT wants to be able to make big rate concessions to its largestcustomers and cut rates by more than five percent if it needs toin order to remain competitive with MCI and US Sprint.andP;  If the FCCagrees, AT and T will likely cut rates deeply, resulting in eitheranother monopoly or unprofitability for the long-distance carrier.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   American Telephone and Telegraph Co. (rules and regulations).andO;Ticker:    T.andO;Topic:     DeregulationUnited States. Federal Communications CommissionTelephone companiesPricing PolicyPrice CuttingGovernment RegulationCommunications Service Suppliers.andO;Feature:   illustrationcartoon.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>